# Commit messages (Conventional Commits + emoji types)

Canonical rule file: `.cursor/rules/commit-conventions.mdc` — keep both in sync when changing format.

When suggesting, writing, or performing commits for this repo, follow these rules.

## Cursor Agent vs Source Control “sparkle”

- **Agent (chat / tasks):** Prefer the project rule in `.cursor/rules/commit-conventions.mdc` when available.
- **Generate Commit Message (SCM sparkle):** Project Rules are not guaranteed for that feature; it also follows recent **`git log` subjects**. Align branch history with this format, or use **Cursor Settings → Rules → User Rules** for the same wording.

## Format

Use Conventional Commits:

```text
<emoji-type> type(optional-scope): subject
```

- **subject**: short, clear, preferably **English**, **imperative** (add, fix, update — not added/fixed).
- **scope**: optional but recommended when it clarifies the area (e.g. `evaluation`, `okr`, `api`).

### Examples

- `✨ feat(evaluation): add access evaluation report`
- `🩹 fix(okr): resolve progress calculation bug`
- `📝 docs: add branching and MR guidelines`
- `♻️ refactor(api): simplify request validation`

## Mandatory types (use exactly this emoji prefix)

Every commit MUST use **one** of these `type` values with **only** its **paired emoji** from this table at the start of the subject line — **the same emoji for the same type, every time**, for every contributor and every tool (no exceptions).

| Emoji | Type       | Use for                                     |
| ----- | ---------- | ------------------------------------------- |
| 🏗️    | `build`    | Build system or external dependency changes |
| 🌐    | `chore`    | Tasks that do not fit other categories      |
| 👷    | `ci`       | Continuous integration configuration        |
| 📝    | `docs`     | Documentation only                          |
| ✨    | `feat`     | New features / behavior                     |
| 🩹    | `fix`      | Bug fixes                                   |
| ⚡️    | `perf`     | Performance improvements                    |
| ♻️    | `refactor` | Refactor without behavior change            |
| ⏪️    | `revert`   | Revert a previous commit                    |
| 💄    | `style`    | Formatting, whitespace, style-only          |
| 🧪    | `test`     | Tests (add/update)                          |

### Strict emoji–type pairing (everyone must follow)

- **All contributors** must use **only** the emojis in the table above, **exactly paired** with the listed `type` for each commit — no other emoji for that intent, **no swapping** emoji between types, and **no** commits without the leading emoji.
- **Do not substitute** visually similar glyphs (different sparkles/hearts/tools, skin-tone variants intended for another symbol, etc.); copy the emoji from this table **verbatim** each time.

Full line pattern (with optional scope):

`🩹 fix(scope): describe the fix in imperative English`

## Quality

- **Atomic**: one clear intent per commit.
- Avoid vague subjects: `update`, `fix stuff`, `changes`, `wip`.
- Split large work into **multiple small commits** when reasonable.
- Add **scope** when it helps (`feat(auth): ...`).

## Tools and hooks

- **Do not** use `git commit --no-verify` or any `-n` / flags that **skip commit hooks** or validation.
- Local validation: `.githooks/commit-msg` and `scripts/validate-commit-msg.js` (when `core.hooksPath` is set to `.githooks`).
- Do not encourage shallow or non-conforming messages to “just push” via the terminal.

## Assistant behavior

- When generating a commit message, output a **single compliant line** (or title + optional body below a blank line if the change needs detail), using the **exact** emoji from the mandatory table for the chosen `type`.
- If the change mixes unrelated concerns, **recommend splitting** into separate commits with correct types/emojis.
